						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Another funny trick is you can define a segment that will output in the file in one memory block, but be linked with a program counter as if it belongs in a different memory block. Specifically this is useful for code that you need to copy into RAM before running</div><br />See also <a href="http://www.cc65.org/doc/ld65-5.html#ss5.4" class="postlink">documentation of this ld65 feature</a>. There's a working example in the <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=95846#p95846" class="postlink">Action 53 menu</a>, which needs to copy description text and compressed CHR data from another bank before displaying them. Putting the copying code into RAM keeps it running while it switches to another 32K bank.</div>

